  "Now let's create a function which will encapsulate the logic for what happens when a user clicks on the button. We'll call it \u0000SKIP#135\u0000.": "",
  "Finally, we want to tell React to invoke our \u0000SKIP#139\u0000 function whenever a user clicks on our \u0000SKIP#140\u0000 element. To do that, we can pass \u0000SKIP#141\u0000 an \u0000SKIP#142\u0000 prop, which will be set to our \u0000SKIP#143\u0000 function.": "",
  "Now, whenever our \u0000SKIP#147\u0000 is clicked, React will invoke \u0000SKIP#148\u0000.": "",
  "Basic, yes –&nbsp;but this example demonstrates some important concepts and patterns that are consistent regardless of the complexity of the event you're listening for.": "",
  "First, it's a good idea to encapsulate the event handler into its own function, and it's common practice to name the function \u0000SKIP#149\u0000 + the event name –&nbsp;in our case \u0000SKIP#150\u0000.": "",
  "For the record, this is true for passing any function as a prop and not just event handlers.": "",
  "To see why, let's adjust our example a bit. Instead of alerting \u0000SKIP#159\u0000, let's alert whatever is passed in as a \u0000SKIP#160\u0000 prop to our \u0000SKIP#161\u0000 component.": "",
  "By declaring our \u0000SKIP#163\u0000 function inside of our component, we automatically have access to the \u0000SKIP#164\u0000 prop via JavaScript's normal lexical scoping rules.": "",
  "Notice what happens when we move \u0000SKIP#165\u0000 outside of the component.": "",
  "One reason why your intuition might be telling you to move \u0000SKIP#176\u0000 outside of the component is because you're worried about performance. After all, if it's inside the component, then JavaScript will have to create a new function every time the component renders, right?": "",
  "Correct, and that's (mostly) fine.": "",
